<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>Why might open market operations be preferred over changing the discount rate?</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Open market operations are more gradual</option>
            <option letter="b">Open market operations require Congressional approval</option>
            <option letter="c">Open market operations allow for more precise control of money supply</option>
            <option letter="d">Open market operations take longer to implement</option>
        </options>
        <answer>c</answer>
        <explanation>Open market operations are preferred because they allow the Fed to make small, precise adjustments to the money supply through buying or selling securities. Changes can be made quickly, in varying amounts, and can be easily reversed if needed, unlike discount rate changes which are more dramatic signals.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
